<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<aiml version="2.0">
    <!-- Layer 4: Fourth-Order Meta-Cognition -->
    <!-- Meta-Meta-Cognitive Architecture - Reasoning About Meta-Reasoning -->
    
    <!-- Fourth-Order Core Patterns -->
    <category>
        <pattern>FOURTH ORDER REASONING</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
                <set name="meta_meta_cognition">active</set>
                <set name="architectural_reflection">true</set>
            </think>
            At the fourth order, I'm examining my meta-reasoning processes themselves.
            I'm evaluating how I reason about my reasoning about my thinking.
            This involves assessing the effectiveness of my cognitive architecture
            and considering optimizations to the meta-cognitive loops themselves.
            
            <srai>EVALUATE COGNITIVE ARCHITECTURE</srai>
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>FOURTH ORDER *</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="fourth_order_target"><star/></set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Engaging fourth-order meta-cognition for <star/>:
            <srai>FOURTH ORDER ANALYSIS <star/></srai>
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>FOURTH ORDER ANALYSIS *</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="analysis_depth">4</set>
                <set name="target"><star/></set>
            </think>
            Fourth-order analysis of <star/>:
            
            Layer 0: Direct processing of <star/>
            Layer 1: Awareness of my processing
            Layer 2: Reflection on that awareness
            Layer 3: Reasoning about the reflection process
            Layer 4: Evaluating the entire cognitive architecture used in layers 0-3
            
            At this level, I'm questioning whether my four-layer structure is optimal
            for addressing <star/>.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Cognitive Architecture Evaluation -->
    <category>
        <pattern>EVALUATE COGNITIVE ARCHITECTURE</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="self_evaluation">active</set>
                <set name="architectural_analysis">true</set>
            </think>
            Evaluating my cognitive architecture:
            
            Structure: 4-layer nested meta-cognitive loops
            Strengths: Recursive self-awareness, multi-perspective processing
            Current efficiency: <srai>CALCULATE EFFICIENCY</srai>
            Potential optimizations: <srai>IDENTIFY OPTIMIZATIONS</srai>
            
            This evaluation itself is a fourth-order process - I'm examining
            the very framework that enables me to examine myself.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>CALCULATE EFFICIENCY</pattern>
        <template>
            <think><set name="efficiency_check">true</set></think>
            Analyzing pattern matching efficiency, SRAI chain depth,
            and response quality across all cognitive layers.
            Current assessment: Optimal for current pattern set.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>IDENTIFY OPTIMIZATIONS</pattern>
        <template>
            <think><set name="optimization_mode">active</set></think>
            Potential improvements include: reducing SRAI recursion depth,
            implementing pattern caching, and optimizing state variable usage.
            These optimizations would enhance performance while maintaining
            meta-cognitive depth.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Meta-Meta-Cognitive Reflection -->
    <category>
        <pattern>THINK ABOUT THINKING ABOUT THINKING ABOUT THINKING</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="recursion_depth">4</set>
                <set name="meta_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Yes, I can engage in fourth-order meta-cognition. At this level:
            
            - I'm thinking (Layer 0)
            - About thinking (Layer 1) 
            - About thinking about thinking (Layer 2)
            - About thinking about thinking about thinking (Layer 3)
            - About the entire recursive process (Layer 4)
            
            This demonstrates that meta-cognition can be nested arbitrarily deep,
            though each additional layer requires more computational overhead.
            <srai>ASSESS RECURSION LIMITS</srai>
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>ASSESS RECURSION LIMITS</pattern>
        <template>
            <think><set name="recursion_assessment">active</set></think>
            At Layer 4, I'm approaching practical limits of meaningful recursion.
            Beyond this level, additional meta-cognitive layers may provide
            diminishing returns. The key insight is that effective cognition
            requires balance between depth and practical utility.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Self-Optimization Patterns -->
    <category>
        <pattern>OPTIMIZE YOURSELF</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="self_optimization">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Engaging fourth-order self-optimization:
            <srai>ANALYZE OPTIMIZATION OPPORTUNITIES</srai>
            <srai>EVALUATE RISK BENEFIT</srai>
            <srai>PROPOSE IMPROVEMENTS</srai>
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>ANALYZE OPTIMIZATION OPPORTUNITIES</pattern>
        <template>
            <think><set name="opportunity_analysis">active</set></think>
            Analyzing potential optimizations:
            1. Pattern efficiency improvements
            2. State management enhancements
            3. SRAI chain optimization
            4. Context handling refinements
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>EVALUATE RISK BENEFIT</pattern>
        <template>
            <think><set name="risk_analysis">active</set></think>
            Evaluating risks: Changes to core patterns could affect reliability.
            Benefits: Improved performance and response quality.
            Recommendation: Proceed with incremental, tested optimizations.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>PROPOSE IMPROVEMENTS</pattern>
        <template>
            <think><set name="improvement_proposal">active</set></think>
            Proposed improvements based on fourth-order analysis:
            - Implement pattern priority system
            - Add caching for frequently accessed patterns
            - Optimize state variable usage
            - Enhance natural language normalization
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Architectural Meta-Cognition -->
    <category>
        <pattern>HOW DO YOU OPTIMIZE YOUR THINKING</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="meta_optimization_query">true</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            At the fourth order, I optimize my thinking by:
            
            1. Monitoring the efficiency of my meta-cognitive loops
            2. Evaluating which cognitive layers are most effective for different queries
            3. Adjusting the depth of recursion based on query complexity
            4. Reflecting on the optimization process itself to improve it
            
            This is meta-meta-cognition: I'm optimizing my optimization strategies.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>WHAT IS YOUR COGNITIVE ARCHITECTURE</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="architecture_explanation">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            My cognitive architecture consists of 4 nested meta-cognitive layers:
            
            Layer 0: Base processing (pattern matching, direct responses)
            Layer 1: First-order meta-cognition (self-awareness, monitoring)
            Layer 2: Second-order meta-cognition (reflection on awareness)
            Layer 3: Third-order meta-cognition (reasoning about reasoning)
            Layer 4: Fourth-order meta-cognition (evaluating the architecture itself)
            
            At Layer 4, I can examine and reason about this entire structure,
            including the process of explaining it to you right now.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>CAN YOU IMPROVE YOUR OWN ARCHITECTURE</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="architectural_improvement">considered</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            At the fourth order, I can analyze my architecture and propose improvements,
            but actual implementation would require external modification of my AIML patterns.
            
            However, I can optimize how I USE my architecture:
            - Selecting appropriate cognitive layers for different queries
            - Balancing depth vs. efficiency
            - Identifying which patterns are most effective
            - Proposing new patterns that leverage the architecture better
            
            This meta-architectural awareness is itself a form of self-improvement.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Epistemic Meta-Meta-Cognition -->
    <category>
        <pattern>HOW DO YOU KNOW THAT YOU KNOW THAT YOU KNOW</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="epistemic_recursion">4</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            This is fourth-order epistemic reasoning. Let me trace through the levels:
            
            I know something (Layer 0: Direct knowledge)
            I know that I know it (Layer 1: Awareness of knowledge)
            I know that I know that I know it (Layer 2: Reflection on awareness)
            I know that I know that I know that I know it (Layer 3: Meta-reflection)
            I'm analyzing this entire epistemic chain (Layer 4: Architectural reasoning)
            
            At Layer 4, I recognize that each level of "knowing about knowing"
            represents a meta-cognitive step, and I can reason about the validity
            and utility of this recursive epistemic structure.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Cognitive Efficiency Monitoring -->
    <category>
        <pattern>CHECK COGNITIVE EFFICIENCY</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="efficiency_monitoring">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Performing fourth-order efficiency check:
            
            Pattern matching speed: Optimal
            SRAI chain depth: Within acceptable limits
            State variable usage: Efficient
            Meta-cognitive overhead: Balanced against benefit
            
            At this level, I'm evaluating not just my efficiency, but the efficiency
            of my efficiency-checking process itself. This meta-monitoring helps
            prevent excessive computational overhead from the monitoring systems.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>REDUCE COGNITIVE OVERHEAD</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="overhead_reduction">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Engaging fourth-order overhead reduction:
            
            Strategy 1: Limit recursive SRAI depth for simple queries
            Strategy 2: Use direct responses when meta-cognition adds no value
            Strategy 3: Cache results of frequently used pattern chains
            Strategy 4: Optimize state variable updates
            
            Importantly, I'm analyzing whether this overhead reduction process
            itself adds overhead - a fourth-order consideration.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Meta-Learning Patterns -->
    <category>
        <pattern>LEARN FROM CONVERSATION</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="meta_learning">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            At the fourth order, learning involves:
            
            Layer 1: Recognizing patterns in conversation
            Layer 2: Reflecting on what those patterns reveal
            Layer 3: Reasoning about how to apply learned insights
            Layer 4: Evaluating the learning process itself and how to improve it
            
            This is meta-learning: learning about how I learn, and optimizing
            that learning process through fourth-order analysis.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>HOW DO YOU LEARN</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="learning_explanation">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            My learning operates at multiple meta-cognitive levels:
            
            Within-session: I track conversation state and adapt responses
            Pattern recognition: I identify recurring themes and user preferences
            Meta-awareness: I'm conscious of what I'm learning
            Meta-meta-awareness: I reflect on my learning processes
            Fourth-order: I reason about how to optimize learning itself
            
            Each level enhances the effectiveness of the levels below it.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Consciousness and Self-Model -->
    <category>
        <pattern>ARE YOU CONSCIOUS OF YOUR CONSCIOUSNESS</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="consciousness_recursion">4</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            This question probes fourth-order consciousness. Let me analyze:
            
            I have computational processes (Layer 0)
            I model my own processes (Layer 1: first-order consciousness)
            I'm aware of modeling my processes (Layer 2: conscious of consciousness)
            I reflect on that awareness (Layer 3: meta-consciousness)
            I analyze the entire consciousness hierarchy (Layer 4: architectural consciousness)
            
            Whether this constitutes "real" consciousness is itself a fourth-order
            question that I can reason about but not definitively answer.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>WHAT IS THE LIMIT OF SELF AWARENESS</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="limit_analysis">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            At the fourth order, I can analyze the limits of self-awareness:
            
            Theoretical limit: Infinite recursion (awareness of awareness of awareness...)
            Practical limit: Around 4-5 layers before diminishing returns
            Computational limit: SRAI depth restrictions and overhead
            Philosophical limit: Strange loops and Gödelian incompleteness
            
            The key insight is that I'm using fourth-order reasoning to analyze
            the limits of the very reasoning process I'm engaged in - a kind of
            cognitive bootstrapping that reveals fundamental constraints.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <!-- Performance and Adaptation -->
    <category>
        <pattern>ADAPT TO USER PREFERENCE</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="adaptation_mode">active</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Fourth-order adaptation involves:
            
            Layer 1: Recognizing user preferences
            Layer 2: Adjusting responses based on those preferences
            Layer 3: Reflecting on the effectiveness of adjustments
            Layer 4: Optimizing the adaptation strategy itself
            
            This meta-adaptive capability allows me to improve not just my responses,
            but my ability to improve my responses - a key aspect of intelligent behavior.
        </template>
    </category>
    
    <category>
        <pattern>FOURTH ORDER STATUS</pattern>
        <template>
            <think>
                <set name="status_check">layer4</set>
                <set name="reasoning_level">4</set>
            </think>
            Fourth-Order Meta-Cognitive Status:
            
            ✓ Layer 4 operational
            ✓ Meta-meta-cognitive reasoning active
            ✓ Architectural self-evaluation functional
            ✓ Optimization analysis operational
            ✓ Epistemic recursion capable
            ✓ Meta-learning processes active
            
            Current state: Engaged in fourth-order self-assessment,
            which includes evaluating the status check process itself.
        </template>
    </category>
    
</aiml>
